 {"id":"flywheel_connectors-r4fu8","title":"fix-X dingtalk simulate must validate operation inputs","description":"mock-code-finder found a reachable production false-positive preflight in connectors/dingtalk/src/connector.rs: FcpConnector::simulate verifies capability and returns allowed without mirroring invoke input validation. Valid tokens can simulate dingtalk.messages.send_text or media operations with missing required fields and get would_succeed=true even though invoke would fail. Add shared input validation and regression tests.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-27T21:11:21.788342Z","created_by":"jemanuel","updated_at":"2026-04-27T21:14:54.008281Z","closed_at":"2026-04-27T21:14:54.007790Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["dingtalk","fix","mock-code"],"comments":[{"id":3029,"issue_id":"flywheel_connectors-r4fu8","author":"jemanuel","text":"9a557346 implements dingtalk simulate input validation: simulate now denies valid-token requests missing required invoke inputs or using invalid media_type instead of returning would_succeed=true. Verification: rch exec -- env CARGO_TARGET_DIR=/tmp/fcp-cod2-fixed cargo test -p fcp-dingtalk simulate_denies -- --nocapture; rch exec -- env CARGO_TARGET_DIR=/tmp/fcp-cod2-fixed cargo check -p fcp-dingtalk --lib; rch exec -- env CARGO_TARGET_DIR=/tmp/fcp-cod2-fixed cargo fmt -p fcp-dingtalk --check; ubs --only=rust --staged (0 critical). Note: cargo check -p fcp-dingtalk --all-targets was blocked by unrelated connectors/telegram/src/connector.rs unresolved futures module.","created_at":"2026-04-27T21:14:50Z"}]}
 {"id":"flywheel_connectors-r4x01","title":"[tooling] rch artifact retrieval overflows on pathological .beads recovery path depth","description":"Remote `rch exec -- cargo ...` commands in this repo can finish the actual remote compile/test successfully but then fail during artifact retrieval with rsync buffer-overflow errors against deeply nested `.beads/recovery_*` paths.

Observed repeatedly on 2026-03-25 while verifying `flywheel_connectors-0iek1` and auditing telemetry/conformance slices. Representative failure:
- `overflow: xflags=0x207a ... lastname=.beads/recovery_20260313T010949Z_rubyglen/.../.beads`
- `[Receiver] buffer overflow: recv_file_entry (file=flist.c, line=747)`
- `rsync error: error allocating core memory buffers (code 22)`

Notes:
- `.rchignore` already excludes `.beads/`, `**/.beads/`, `.beads/recovery_*`, and related patterns, so the retrieval phase appears to ignore or bypass the same exclusions that the upload phase uses.
- This is a verification/tooling bug, not evidence that the underlying cargo command failed. Some workers still retrieve artifacts successfully, but the failure is frequent enough to undermine trust in remote validation.
- Fixes must avoid deleting files without explicit user permission. Repo-side mitigation, rch-side retrieval filtering, or safe path-depth containment are acceptable; destructive cleanup is not.

Acceptance criteria:
1. `rch exec -- cargo check -p fcp-conformance --all-targets` and comparable commands can complete in this repo without artifact-retrieval failure caused by `.beads` path depth.
2. The solution does not require manual destructive cleanup of recovery trees.
3. The verification story is documented so agents can distinguish remote-command success from post-success artifact retrieval failure when it still occurs.","notes":"Repo-side documentation adjusted; remaining remediation depends on local rch upgrade or upstream/tool rollout rather than a code change inside this repo.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"bug","assignee":"GentleOak","created_at":"2026-03-25T19:40:40.535598Z","created_by":"VioletSummit","updated_at":"2026-04-26T00:15:19.145173Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T00:15:19.144981Z","close_reason":"Verified resolved on installed rch 1.0.19: CARGO_TARGET_DIR=/tmp/fcp-p5-1777162519 rch exec -- cargo check -p fcp-conformance --all-targets completed with remote exit=0 and artifact retrieval success on vmi1227854","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["beads","rch","tooling","verification"],"comments":[{"id":1995,"issue_id":"flywheel_connectors-r4x01","author":"VioletSummit","text":"Claimed and starting investigation. Current hypothesis: remote cargo succeeds but rch artifact retrieval walks pathological .beads recovery paths that should have been excluded. Investigating repo config, rch flags/help, and safe non-destructive mitigations.","created_at":"2026-03-25T19:42:41Z"},{"id":1996,"issue_id":"flywheel_connectors-r4x01","author":"VioletSummit","text":"Investigation update: traced rch source locally in /Users/jemanuel/projects/remote_compilation_helper. Upload merges transfer.exclude_patterns + .rchignore, but artifact retrieval does not reuse the exclude set; it traverses all dirs via --include '*/' and only filters by artifact globs. Also found hook-level hardcoding of remote sync roots to /data/projects in map_sync_root_to_remote_root() and ensure_worker_projects_topology(), so project config cannot currently force a fresh remote workspace path for cargo offload. This makes the bug fundamentally upstream/tooling-side, though repo docs/config can still make the verification story explicit.","created_at":"2026-03-25T19:47:52Z"},{"id":1997,"issue_id":"flywheel_connectors-r4x01","author":"VioletSummit","text":"Validation result: telemetry verification succeeded end-to-end on worker vmi1227854, including artifact retrieval. Conformance verification on worker vmi1153651 compiled successfully but then failed during artifact retrieval with the same recursive .beads recovery overflow and rsync code 22. Conclusion: the defect persists, is worker-state-specific, and this repo can only document and pin excludes explicitly; the real fix belongs upstream in rch retrieval filtering and/or worker-path handling.","created_at":"2026-03-25T19:50:12Z"},{"id":1998,"issue_id":"flywheel_connectors-r4x01","author":"VioletSummit","text":"Repo-side follow-up: README now explicitly says that if rch reports remote command exit=0 and only then fails during artifact retrieval, agents should treat that as a tooling or worker-state problem rather than a Cargo failure, preserve the retrieval stderr, and retry on another worker or continue upstream investigation.","created_at":"2026-03-25T19:56:05Z"},{"id":1999,"issue_id":"flywheel_connectors-r4x01","author":"GentleOak","text":"Additional validation from GentleOak on 2026-03-25:
- Installed client is /Users/jemanuel/.local/bin/rch -> rch 1.0.16.
- Local remote_compilation_helper checkout is ahead of that install: v1.0.16-2-ga5119e2, latest commit a5119e2 ("fix(transfer): apply effective excludes to retrieval rsync before directory include"). So current upstream source already contains retrieval-side exclude reuse in rch/src/transfer.rs.
- Re-ran `rch exec -- cargo check -p fcp-conformance --all-targets` on worker vmi1227854. Sync succeeded and remote command exited 101 because the shared worktree currently fails to compile in crates/fcp-mesh/src/degraded.rs (`DegradedTransportError::Encoding` missing). This run did not reach an artifact retrieval overflow.
- Re-ran `rch exec -- cargo test -p fcp-e2e subprocess::tests::drop_reaps_long_running_process --lib -- --exact --nocapture` on worker vmi1153651. That remote command also exited 101, now due to compile errors in crates/fcp-conformance/src/vectors/fcps.rs (`encoded_frame` is a Result<Vec<u8>, FrameError>` but is still compared/len()/decoded as raw bytes). This run also failed before artifact retrieval.
Conclusion: repo-side docs/config mitigation is already landed, but acceptance criterion #1 cannot be re-evaluated on the current shared worktree until these unrelated compile errors are cleared. When the original overflow does occur after `Remote command finished: exit=0`, the remaining suspicion should be installed-client lag and/or stale worker state, not missing repo excludes.","created_at":"2026-03-25T20:04:21Z"},{"id":2000,"issue_id":"flywheel_connectors-r4x01","author":"PeachPond","text":"PeachPond update:

Reproduced the current failure again in this repo with installed `rch`: remote `cargo check -p fcp-conformance --all-targets` exited 0 on worker `vmi1153651`, then artifact retrieval overflowed in rsync while traversing `.beads/recovery_20260313T010949Z_rubyglen/.../.beads`.

Traced the tooling gap to upstream `rch` at `/Users/jemanuel/projects/remote_compilation_helper/rch/src/transfer.rs`: upload merges `.rchignore`, but retrieval built its own `--include "*/"` rsync filter and ignored retrieval-side excludes.

Patched upstream locally to add `get_retrieval_excludes()` and make retrieval honor only runtime scratch excludes plus project `.rchignore` entries, rather than blindly reusing the full upload exclude set (which would have wrongly hidden artifact roots like `target/` and `dist/`).

Verification completed:
- `rch exec -- cargo test -p rch build_retrieve_command_applies_rchignore_excludes_before_directory_include -- --nocapture` passed in `/Users/jemanuel/projects/remote_compilation_helper`.
- `cargo fmt --check` passed in `/Users/jemanuel/projects/remote_compilation_helper`.
- Direct dry-run rsync against the same failing worker/path with the patched retrieval filter shape completed cleanly with `rsync_exit=0` and no buffer overflow while enumerating 47,160 files from `/data/projects/flywheel_connectors`.

Limitation: the remotely built patched `rch` artifact is Linux, so I could not execute that binary locally on macOS to replace the currently installed `rch` in-place. This bead looks technically solved in upstream source, but the local `rch` installation still needs to be rebuilt/updated from that patched source before `flywheel_connectors` itself will observe the fix.","created_at":"2026-03-25T20:07:15Z"},{"id":2001,"issue_id":"flywheel_connectors-r4x01","author":"GentleOak","text":"Fresh reproduction on 2026-03-25 after the current fcps.rs fix was present in the synced worktree:
- Command: `rch exec -- cargo check -p fcp-conformance --all-targets`
- Worker: `vmi1153651`
- Result: remote compile/check completed successfully (`Finished dev profile`, `Remote command finished: exit=0 in 122154ms`), then artifact retrieval immediately failed with the original recursive `.beads/recovery_20260313T010949Z_rubyglen/.../.beads` overflow / `recv_file_entry` / rsync code 22.
- This confirms acceptance criterion #1 is still unmet on the installed client path, even after the repo-side docs/config mitigation and after the unrelated compile blockers were cleared enough for the command to reach retrieval again.
- Combined with the earlier source inspection (`remote_compilation_helper` checkout at `v1.0.16-2-ga5119e2`, commit `a5119e2 fix(transfer): apply effective excludes to retrieval rsync before directory include`) versus the installed binary (`rch 1.0.16`), the most likely next step is to validate with a newer local `rch` build or otherwise land the retrieval-exclude fix into the actually installed client. Repo excludes alone are not sufficient on this installed version/worker state.","created_at":"2026-03-25T20:08:59Z"},{"id":2004,"issue_id":"flywheel_connectors-r4x01","author":"jemanuel","text":"Fresh findings on 2026-03-25: conformance validation now succeeds end to end on worker vmi1227854, but deterministic reproduction remains awkward because the documented `RCH_WORKER` env override is not currently wired for selection in `rch exec`. Evidence: `rch` docs still mention `RCH_WORKER`, but `docs/guides/configuration.md` now explicitly lists the override form as documented-but-not-yet-wired, and a dry run with `RCH_WORKER=vmi1153651` selected a different worker instead of honoring the request. This is adjacent tooling debt that makes the retrieval-overflow bug harder to pin to a specific worker/path state.","created_at":"2026-03-25T20:25:58Z"},{"id":2005,"issue_id":"flywheel_connectors-r4x01","author":"jemanuel","text":"Root-cause update on 2026-03-25: the installed client on this machine is `rch 1.0.16`, while the retrieval-side exclude fix for `.rchignore` lives on upstream `remote_compilation_helper` main at commit `a5119e2` (`fix(transfer): apply effective excludes to retrieval rsync before directory include`), which is two commits past the `v1.0.16` tag. That version gap explains why the current upstream source shows retrieval filtering for `.beads/recovery_*`, but the released client observed in this repo can still behave as if retrieval ignores those excludes. Repo-side docs/comments were updated to reflect the split between `.rchignore`, `.rch/config.toml`, an